Feature: a BC boots under an ephemeral in-container fabro server with launch-interface parity to bc-container

  Fabro launch-interface parity — ADR-050 (KEPT vs REPLACED P1-P20 launch properties,
  the readiness-barrier seam, the engage-tier replacement), Anchored on ADR-048 (fabro as
  the alternable in-container BC-orchestration substrate). Evidence: findings/fabro-spike/
  01-targets-spec.md + 01a-target-launch-parity.md (20 properties / 3 tiers) and 04-goal-demo.md
  section 3 invariant #3 (a BC booted from the same shopsystem-bc-base:latest the three
  healthy infra BCs run). Fabro runs as an ephemeral LOCAL server (provider=local, 127.0.0.1)
  inside one bc-base container; it REPLACES the engage-tier / tmux-inject engagement with the
  run-graph launch entry path but KEEPS the image, credential-proxy, postgres DSN and the
  real registered EMPTY-mailbox starting posture. This is a LEAD-PROCESS contract pin:
  fabro in-container orchestration is not yet an owned BC, so there is no BC addressee; it is
  NOT dispatchable via assign_scenarios and is flagged for the discriminator as the scenario
  most BC-adjacent should a fabro-orchestration BC ever be created. Distinct from
  features/bc-launcher 33/34/35/48 (bc-container launch gates), which this does not duplicate.
  @scenario_hash:1aeace4c593ab14f
  Scenario: a BC boots under an ephemeral in-container fabro server and clears the KEPT launch-parity surface
    Given an ephemeral in-container fabro server running provider=local on 127.0.0.1 inside a shopsystem-bc-base:latest container
    When the fabro run-graph enters its launch entry path for one BC loop
    Then the BC presents a real registered postgres mailbox that starts empty
    And the BC boots from the same shopsystem-bc-base:latest image the infra BCs run
    And the launch traverses the KEPT parity surface prime, health, arm, classify in order
    And no tmux-inject engage-tier engagement is used, that surface being replaced by the run-graph entry path
